    <patterns>
      <pattern>Fire-and-forget endpoint pattern: validate and enqueue in the endpoint handler; return 202 immediately; process in IHostedService or Channel consumer; follow existing pattern in Sprk.Bff.Api for async job processing</pattern>
      <pattern>AI Search document upload: `searchIndexClient.GetSearchClient("playbook-embeddings").UploadDocumentsAsync(new[] { doc })` — follow SemanticSearchService indexing pattern</pattern>
      <pattern>De-duplication: `searchClient.DeleteDocumentsAsync("playbookId", new[] { playbookId })` before uploading new document — or use merge-or-upload with playbookId as the document key</pattern>
      <pattern>Embedding generation: use the raw detection IChatClient (or the embedding model endpoint) — check if an embedding-specific client already exists in the agent factory</pattern>
    </patterns>
  </knowledge>

  <context>
    <background>
      The PlaybookDispatcher (Task R2-015) uses the `playbook-embeddings` AI Search index for Stage 1
      vector similarity search. For this to work, each playbook must have its embedding pre-computed
      and indexed. Task R2-003 created the index schema and initially indexed existing playbooks.
      This task creates the ongoing maintenance pipeline: whenever a playbook is created or updated
      (by an admin in the playbook management UI), its embedding is refreshed in the index.

      The unresolved question in the spec about synchronous vs async indexing: the answer for R2 is
      async (fire-and-forget). The trigger endpoint returns 202 immediately; the caller (Dataverse
      plugin or webhook) does not wait for indexing to complete. There will be a brief window
      (seconds to minutes) of eventual consistency after a playbook update.

      The existing `Services/Ai/Indexing/` directory may already contain document indexing infrastructure
      from R1 — reuse its patterns for the background processing queue and AI Search client usage.
    </background>
    <dependencies>
      Depends on Task R2-003 (playbook-embeddings AI Search index) and R2-006 (Phase 1 deployment).
      Independent of Group A tasks and other Group B tasks — safe for parallel execution. Does not
      need to complete before PlaybookDispatcher (R2-015) can be implemented since R2-015 uses the
      index that R2-003 pre-populated. Own files: new `PlaybookIndexingService.cs` and the trigger
      endpoint handler.
    </dependencies>
  </context>

  <steps>
    <step order="0">Read `Services/Ai/Indexing/` to understand existing indexing infrastructure and background processing patterns</step>
    <step order="1">Read `SemanticSearchService.cs` to understand how to write documents to AI Search indices</step>
    <step order="2">Determine how embedding generation is currently done (check for an embedding client or text-embedding-3-large integration in the existing BFF)</step>
    <step order="3">Create `PlaybookIndexingService.cs` in `Services/Ai/Indexing/` with a method `IndexPlaybookAsync(string playbookId, CancellationToken ct)`</step>
    <step order="4">Implement Dataverse fetch: retrieve playbook record by ID including `sprk_triggerPhrases`, `sprk_recordType`, `sprk_entityType`, `sprk_tags` fields</step>
    <step order="5">Implement text concatenation for embedding: `{name}\n{description}\n{triggerPhrases}\n{tags}`</step>
    <step order="6">Call embedding model to generate 3072-dimension vector for the concatenated text</step>
    <step order="7">Implement de-duplication: delete existing `playbook-embeddings` entry for this playbookId (use merge-or-upload pattern if available in AI Search SDK)</step>
    <step order="8">Write new document to `playbook-embeddings` index with all required fields</step>
    <step order="9">Create `POST /api/ai/playbooks/{playbookId}/index` Minimal API endpoint that enqueues indexing and returns 202 Accepted immediately</step>
    <step order="10">Wire error handling: catch embedding/indexing exceptions, log Warning with playbookId only (no content), leave stale entry in place on failure</step>
    <step order="11">Run `dotnet build` and verify no errors</step>
    <step order="12">Update TASK-INDEX.md: change task R2-016 status to completed (🔲 → ✅)</step>
  </steps>

  <tools>
    <tool>dotnet</tool>
    <tool>git</tool>
  </tools>

  <outputs>
    <artifact type="code">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Indexing/PlaybookIndexingService.cs — background service that generates embeddings and writes to playbook-embeddings index</artifact>
    <artifact type="code">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Api/Ai/ (new file or addition) — POST /api/ai/playbooks/{playbookId}/index trigger endpoint</artifact>
  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion testable="true">`POST /api/ai/playbooks/{playbookId}/index` returns `202 Accepted` within 100ms (before embedding generation starts)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">After the endpoint is called, the playbook appears in the `playbook-embeddings` index within 30 seconds (eventual consistency)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">If the same playbookId is indexed twice, only one entry exists in the index (de-duplication working)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">If embedding generation fails, the BFF logs a Warning with playbookId but does NOT propagate the error to the HTTP caller</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">No playbook content (name, description, trigger phrases) appears in logs beyond the playbookId identifier (ADR-015)</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`dotnet build` passes with no errors</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>

  <notes>
    Check whether the Azure OpenAI text-embedding-3-large deployment name is configured in the BFF
    `appsettings.json` or `AiOptions`. Use the existing configuration rather than hardcoding the
    deployment name. The deployment name from `docs/architecture/auth-AI-azure-resources.md` is
    the reference — use it.

    The `POST /api/ai/playbooks/{playbookId}/index` endpoint will eventually be called by a Dataverse
    plugin (post-create/post-update on `sprk_analysisplaybook`). For Phase 2, the plugin wiring is
    not required — just the endpoint. Document the expected call pattern in
    `notes/016-playbook-indexing-trigger.md` for the Dataverse plugin developer.
  </notes>

